System-Dynamic Modeling of Cognitive Regulation and Synaptic Homeostasis: A Computational Framework for Feedback, Energy Balance, and Adaptive Control

Abstract

Human cognitive performance emerges from complex interactions between neural regulation, metabolic constraints, environmental conditions, learning processes, and behavioral feedback mechanisms. This work introduces a computational systems framework for modeling cognitive regulation as a dynamic feedback-control problem.

The proposed model represents an agent state as a multidimensional vector:

S(t) = [P(t), E(t), D(t)]

where P(t) describes task-oriented cognitive output, E(t) represents available energetic and regulatory resources, and D(t) represents accumulated system stress or degradation. Temporal evolution is modeled through coupled difference equations incorporating external modulation factors, resource consumption, recovery processes, and adaptive regulation.

A central concept of this framework is "kinetic balance": cognitive modulators are modeled as changes in regulatory gain within an existing biological control system rather than as external sources of energy. This distinction allows the simulation of situations where increased signal efficiency may improve task performance while maintaining constraints imposed by biological resource availability and homeostatic regulation.

The framework incorporates a probabilistic uncertainty layer to distinguish:


Epistemic uncertainty arising from incomplete information.

Aleatoric uncertainty arising from biological variability.

Structural uncertainty arising from model assumptions and simplifications.

A multi-agent validation architecture is proposed to improve transparency and reproducibility. Independent analytical roles evaluate model assumptions, statistical consistency, biological plausibility, and potential falsification pathways.

The objective is not to replace experimental neuroscience, but to provide an open computational environment for generating, comparing, and testing hypotheses related to cognitive regulation, adaptive control, and system resilience.

Future research directions include parameter estimation from empirical datasets, comparison with established computational neuroscience models, simulation-based hypothesis generation, and open-science replication studies.


